<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-16T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-16T17:00:00-05:00" n="331" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/315</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-16T18:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>7313. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                            <p>No. 355. Your No. 416, Embassy No. 9475, April 12, 11 p.m. We have
                                been forcing vessels proceeding to the Plate to load coal for the
                                railways and other purposes so that there has accumulated large
                                tonnage of general cargo, which tends to congest railways and
                                shipping terminals. We are being urged by Argentina to pursue a more
                                liberal policy in exports to Argentina. Swedish vessels proceeding
                                direct would make small saving in time; but would require bunkers
                                from stations where Allied tonnage has been used for coal
                                transportation instead of from American ports. We seriously object
                                to Swedish vessels proceeding in ballast, which results in an
                                economic, as well as tonnage waste. We nevertheless leave the matter
                                in your hands for final determination.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>